english:
  title: Letter to General Manager Jeon
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I am ashamed of my lack of strategy and cunning, having long enjoyed undeserved favor and rank. I have held the heavy authority of Han's laws and climbed to the highest office of Qin's bureaucracy, yet have found no opportunity to demonstrate my worth. How can I atone for such unmerited greed? Since bandits invaded and our capital fell, I have guarded this vital threshold for years without achieving even the smallest success. Though I held great military power, it proved impossible to act upon it; I failed to repay the Emperor's grace, and this shame burns upon my face.

    Moreover, private resentments have stirred in chambers, and rival powers rise without measure. Lu Xun is remembered only as a capable administrator, while Cui Xian ultimately earned the Emperor's displeasure for his foolishness—accusations were made and denied, and words became weapons to fear. Fortunately, you have taken pity on me, sheltering me with your trust and protecting me with all your strength. Though I have endured harsh criticism, I have escaped ruinous charges. I should spend my remaining days in longing for my post, refining myself in service, and measuring out my life in devotion—never shirking in public duty.

    Yet my strength for maintaining health has grown thin, and years of service have worn me down. My teeth have grayed and my spirit wanes. Though I speak of few desires and little greed, can I truly claim to be a gentleman? My many ailments have made me love leisure—perhaps I have become like the ancients. One cannot force the mind to greater strength, nor can one distribute honor carelessly. To keep my position would obstruct worthier men; I should only seek retirement.

    Now that the palace has been purged and the rebel's nest destroyed, that bows are laid aside and war ceases, that robes of peace fall and governance flourishes—now when worthy talents should be entrusted with power, what place is there for one like me? I am but cold ash that no longer burns, a dried well that none would visit. My past campaigns, though I played my part, now weigh upon me as unearned salary and undeserved rice. Having lost the authority to command ten chariots, how can I lie resting while others defend the realm?

    I humbly submit this memorial and earnestly beg to resign my position. I beseech you to see in me one who speaks truth plainly, and follows the principle that advancement is easy but retreat is difficult. Sway the Emperor's heart toward my desire, and grant this foolish petition. I make no flattering smiles or crooked bows—nor will I harbor resentment to my dying breath. I ask only to witness the peace that spreads across all lands, that I might find one hill where I can age in quiet. I have soiled your unstained virtue; my shame runs deep. I submit this with utmost reverence.
  footnotes:
    - Lu Xun (陸遜) and Cui Xian (崔暹) are historical figures referenced as cautionary examples of officials whose fates warn against remaining in power too long.
    - The references to 'Han's laws' and 'Qin's office' are classical allusions to high bureaucratic rank, not literal references to those dynasties.
    - The imagery of 'cold ash' and 'dried well' conveys the speaker's sense of exhaustion and diminished utility to the state.
